{"slug": "hierophant", "root": "hierophant", "category": "profession", "gloss": "an interpreter of sacred mystery", "definition": "A hierophant reveals sacred things — the presiding priest who displays the holy objects and interprets the mystery to initiates. Unlike a diviner, who extracts hidden knowledge from signs, the hierophant guards knowledge already revealed and admits others into it. His office is disclosure under authority, not prediction.", "history": "The word is Greek *hierophantēs*, 'revealer of holy things' (*hieros*, 'sacred,' plus *phainein*, 'to show') — the chief priest of the Eleusinian Mysteries who showed the sacred objects to the initiated. The turn came through Neoplatonism: as Szönyi shows, later philosophy turned the philosopher into a hierophant, recasting the priest of ritual disclosure as the sage who unveils divine reality, and Renaissance thinkers linked the word to the manifestation of the sacred. It lands as a title for the master of initiation — and, in the Tarot, the fifth trump.", "def_sources": [{"label": "RenaissanceMagicDB, s.v. hierophany", "where": "RenaissanceMagicDB"}, {"label": "Szönyi, John Dee's Occultism", "where": "Renaissance magic (PDF)"}, {"label": "Etymonline, s.v. hierophant (Greek hierophantēs)", "where": "Etymology reference"}], "is_keyword": false, "etymology": {"lang": "Greek", "origin": "Greek hierophantēs 'revealer of holy things' (hieros 'sacred' + phainein 'to show')", "first": "1670s", "note": "The chief priest of the Eleusinian Mysteries, who displayed the sacred objects. Now also a Tarot trump.", "hook": "The priest who ran antiquity's secret rites."}, "essay": null, "sources": ["Etymonline (Douglas Harper)", "Wiktionary", "classical lexica (Lewis & Short, LSJ, Bosworth–Toller)", "Ted's historical-magic DBs (WitchcraftStudiesDB, AgrippaDOP, MedievalMagicDB)"], "stats": {"flavor_total": 2, "oracle_total": 0, "in_flavor_cards": 2, "in_oracle_cards": 0, "name_match_count": 8, "by_variant": {"hierophant": 2